 a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Metz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i>, composed of ancient Germanic <i>maht</i> ‘might, strength’ + <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from Metz in Lorraine, which took its name from a Gaulish tribe, the <i>Mediomatrici</i>; in the name of the place this became abbreviated to <i>Mettis</i>, hence the modern name.","German: from <i>Mätz</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mette","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz  ).","North German: occupational name for a miller, from Middle Low German <i>matte</i>, <i>mette</i> ‘dry measure’.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>mete</i> ‘boundary stone, boundary’ (from Latin <i>meta</i> ‘bounded estate’)."]},{"name":"Metzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Metz (see   Metz  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a bricklayer, Middle Dutch <i>metsere</i>."]},{"name":"Metts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Metz  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Metze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Gerhard, Gernot.","German:","metronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz   1)."]}]},{"name":"Liudgard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ledgard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ledgard","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from the Middle English male or female personal name <i>Legard</i> (Old French <i>Legard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Leudgard</i>, <i>Liudgard</i>, or its female equivalent <i>Leudgarda</i>, <i>Liudgarda</i>). These derive from the elements <i>leud</i> ‘people’ + <i>gard</i> ‘protective enclosure, yard’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Liudgard von Egisheim und von Dagsburg und von Metz was born in 1141, in Leuven, Brabant, Belgium, her father, Hugo X. von Dagsburg, was 14 and her mother, Luitgard von Sulzbach, was 32. She married Dietrich von Are-Hochstaden und von Wickrath about 1170. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1194, in Germany, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1141–1194":"1141–1194","1157–1211":"1157–1211","1150–1197":"1150–1197","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1175–1266":"1175–1266","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Surnud","1127–1178":"1127–1178","1109–1162":"1109–1162","environ 1165":"umbes 1165","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1141":"1141","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","UM 1170":"umbes 1170","1127":"1127","1225":"1225","um 1143":"umbes 1143","2 January 1162":"2. jaanuar 1162","1157":"1157","1178":"1178","1266":"1266","1211":"1211","UM 1155":"umbes 1155","NACH 1194":"pärast 1194","1109":"1109","Leuven, Brabant, Belgium":"Leuven, Brabant, Belgia","Hostaden, Germany":"Saksamaa","Neuchateau, Liège, Belgium":"Neufchâteau, Liège, Belgia"},"fi":{"1141–1194":"1141–1194","1157–1211":"1157–1211","1150–1197":"1150–1197","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1175–1266":"1175–1266","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Kuollut","1127–1178":"1127–1178","1109–1162":"1109–1162","environ 1165":"noin 1165","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1141":"1141","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","UM 1170":"noin 1170","1127":"1127","1225":"1225","um 1143":"noin 1143","2 January 1162":"2. tammikuuta 1162","1157":"1157","1178":"1178","1266":"1266","1211":"1211","UM 1155":"noin 1155","NACH 1194":"1194 jälkeen","1109":"1109","Leuven, Brabant, Belgium":"Leuven, Brabant, Belgia","Hostaden, Germany":"Saksa","Neuchateau, Liège, Belgium":"Neufchâteau, Liège, Belgia"},"fr":{"1141–1194":"1141–1194","1157–1211":"1157–1211","1150–1197":"1150–1197","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1175–1266":"1175–1266","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Décédée","1127–1178":"1127–1178","1109–1162":"1109–1162","environ 1165":"environ 1165","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1141":"1141","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","UM 1170":"environ 1170","1127":"1127","1225":"1225","um 1143":"environ 1143","2 January 1162":"2 janvier 1162","1157":"1157","1178":"1178","1266":"1266","1211":"1211","UM 1155":"environ 1155","NACH 1194":"après 1194","1109":"1109